Anatomy of a Pop Song in the 2010s


William Schulmeister and Rohith Venkatesh

Introduction
¶

Billboard Year-End charts are a cumulative measure of a single or album's performance in the United States, based upon the Billboard magazine charts during any given chart year. The site is a leading figure in the music industry for ranking albums, artists, songs and even providing news. The Year-End chart, accumulated based on radio play, online streaming and album sales, is as good a metric as any to analyze the popular trends of music.

The goal of this experiment is to analyze the anatomy of all the songs of the last 10 years that charted on the Year-End list based on their characteristics from the Spotify API. We compile all the audio features given to us by Spotify and attempt to form a model to ultimately predict a song's position on the Billboard year-end chard, giving some order to the chaotic nature of popular music.

We assert that there is some relationship between year and a song's characteristics that predicts popularity on Spotify and then another relationship between year and popularity that determines the ultimate rank.

Can you reverse engineer a pop song?¶

In [223]:
songs = []
artists = []
ranks = []
years = []
for YEAR in range(2010,2020):
    req = requests.get("https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/{}/hot-100-songs".format(YEAR))
    raw = bs(req.content, 'html.parser')
    s = raw.findAll("div",{"class":"ye-chart-item__title"})
    a = raw.findAll("div",{"class":"ye-chart-item__artist"})
    r = raw.findAll("div",{"class":"ye-chart-item__rank"})

    songs.extend([i.text.strip() for i in s])
    artists.extend([i.text.strip() for i in a])
    ranks.extend([i.text.strip() for i in r])
    years.extend([YEAR for i in r])
df = pd.DataFrame()
df['Rank'] = ranks
df['Song'] = songs
df['Artist'] = artists
df['Year'] = years
df

def get_audio_features(saved_uris):
    artist = []
    track = []
    danceability = []
    energy = []
    key = []
    loudness = []
    mode = []
    speechiness = []
    acousticness = []
    instrumentalness = []
    liveness = []
    valence = []
    tempo = []
    duration_ms = []
    popularity = []
    explicit = []

    for uri in saved_uris:
        if uri is not None:
            x = sp.audio_features(uri)
            y = sp.track(uri)
            for audio_features in x:
                danceability.append(audio_features['danceability'])
                energy.append(audio_features['energy'])
                key.append(audio_features['key'])
                loudness.append(audio_features['loudness'])
                mode.append(audio_features['mode'])
                speechiness.append(audio_features['speechiness'])
                acousticness.append(audio_features['acousticness'])
                instrumentalness.append(audio_features['instrumentalness'])
                liveness.append(audio_features['liveness'])
                valence.append(audio_features['valence'])
                tempo.append(audio_features['tempo'])
                duration_ms.append(audio_features['duration_ms'])

            artist.append(y['album']['artists'][0]['name'])
            track.append(y['name'])
            popularity.append(y['popularity'])
            explicit.append(1 if y['explicit'] == True else 0)
        else: 
            danceability.append(np.nan)
            energy.append(np.nan)
            key.append(np.nan)
            loudness.append(np.nan)
            mode.append(np.nan)
            speechiness.append(np.nan)
            acousticness.append(np.nan)
            instrumentalness.append(np.nan)
            liveness.append(np.nan)
            valence.append(np.nan)
            tempo.append(np.nan)
            duration_ms.append(np.nan)
            artist.append(np.nan)
            track.append(np.nan)
            popularity.append(np.nan)
            explicit.append(np.nan)
            
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    df['artist'] = artist
    df['track'] = track
    df['popularity'] = popularity
    df['danceability'] = danceability
    df['energy'] = energy
    df['key'] = key
    df['loudness'] = loudness
    df['mode'] = mode
    df['speechiness'] = speechiness
    df['acousticness'] = acousticness
    df['instrumentalness'] = instrumentalness
    df['liveness'] = liveness
    df['valence'] = valence
    df['tempo'] = tempo
    df['duration_ms'] = duration_ms
    df['explicit'] = explicit
        
    return df

We define a function that, given a list of Spotify track IDs, can use Spotipy to search each one up and retrieve a number of characteristics. These characteristic are stored in a new DataFrame which is returned. We append a row full of NaNs if the uri given is NoneType. This will be discussed more below, but this is a graceful handling of the case where Spotipy cannot find the track.

In [225]:
exceptions = ['a', 'an', 'of', 'the', 'is', 'but', 'as', 'at',
                    'in', 'on', 'to', 'and', 'from', 'out', 'for', 'with', 'into']
def titlecase(s):  
    word_list = s.split(' ')
    final = [word_list[0][0].capitalize() + word_list[0][1:]]
    for word in word_list[1:]:
        final.append(word if word in exceptions else word[0].capitalize()+word[1:])
    return " ".join(final)

We define a function titlecase, that takes a string s and capitalizes the first letter of each word, provided it is not one of the exceptions which are lowercase in titles.

Note: Python's string.title() function shouldn't be used as it ensures that ONLY the first letter of each word is capitalized. We cannot accept this condition as this format cannot be guaranteed in the names of all artists or songs. For example, ASAP Rocky

In [226]:
def just_the_artist(result):
    if "Featuring" in result:
        result = result.split(" Featuring",1)[0]
    if "&" in result:
        result = result.split(" &",1)[0]
    if ' X' in result:
        result = result.split(' X',1)[0]
    if ' x ' in result:
        result = result.split(' x',1)[0]
    if "/" in result:
        result = result.split(" /",1)[0]
    if "," in result:
        result = result.split(",",1)[0]
    if "+" in result:
        result = result.split(" +",1)[0]
    if "Duet" in result:
        result = result.split(" Duet",1)[0]
    if "With" in result:
        result = result.split(" With",1)[0]
    result = result.replace('*', '')
    result = result.replace('$', 's')
    result = result.replace('AsAP', 'ASAP')
    if 'Fun.' in result or 'fun.' in result: return 'fun.'
    if 'East Movement' in result: return 'Far East Movement'
    if 'Jay-Z' in result or 'Jay Z' in result: return 'JAY-Z'
    if 'Twenty One' in result: return 'twenty one pilots'
    if 'D.R.A.M' in result: return 'DRAM'
    if 'B.o.b' in result: return 'B.o.B'
    if 'Leon' in result: return 'Kings of Leon'
    if 'Will.i.am' in result or 'will.i.am' in result : return 'will.i.am'
    if 'Cash Out' in result: return 'Ca$h Out'
    if '5 Seconds' in result: return '5 Seconds of Summer'
    if 'Zayn' in result: return 'ZAYN'
    return titlecase(result)

We define a utility function to cleanse a string artist for better results in the Spotify API search. The scraped data from Billboard.com cannot be sent straight into the Spotify API as it picky on what is considered the artist of a given song. Despite features and collaborations, the first artist listed is often considered the sole owner of a track. For example, 'California Gurls' by Katy Perry Featuring Snoop Dogg does not exist in Snoop Dogg's discography. For this reason, we cut off anything that could denote a feature.

In addition, we take care of some special cases found from running through the data. These are more cases of format from Billboard and Spotify not agreeing in some cases. This is a rough process and some songs will still fall through because the artist isn't formatted correctly. Some known cases are artists with accented letters in their name like Beyonce or Michael Buble.

In [227]:
def just_the_title(result):
    result = result.replace('$','s')
    if "(" in result:
        result = result.split(" (", 1)[0]
    return result

We define another utility that cleans the song title in a similar way as the previous function cleaned the artist name. We first remove any dollar signs and replace them with s in the case of Ran$som by Lil Tecca and others.

We also provide a fix to some songs that would be dropped because they became popular off a soundtrack. For example, Post Malone's 'Sunflower' charted off the soundtrack for Spiderman: Into the Spiderverse and is therefore listed like that on Billboard. By cutting everything including and after the first '(' which would denote the soundtrack it came from, we change the track name to only 'Sunflower' which can be found on 'Hollywood is Bleeding', Post Malone's most recent album. Unfortunately, some songs like 'Pray for Me' by the Weeknd only appear on the movie soundtrack and therefore can't be found.

In [228]:
def get_album_uris(artist):
    q = '{}'.format(artist)
    results = sp.search(q=q, type = 'album', limit = 20)
    album_uris = []
    for i in range(len(results['albums']['items'])):
            album_uris.append(results['albums']['items'][i]['uri'])
    return album_uris

We define another helper method that takes an artist as a string and searches for their albums using a GET request. It then appends the uris (Uniform Resource Indicator) to a list and returns them. It is important to note that this search returns the first 20 albums that are either by the artist searched or contain the artist in their title.

In [229]:
def find_song(track, uris, artist):
    for i in uris:
        for j in sp.album_tracks(i)['items']:
            if artist in j['artists'][0]['name']:
                if j['name'].startswith(track):
                    uri = j['uri']
                    return uri
    return None

Given a string track, an artist, and a list of album uris found from a call to get_album_uris(), find_song() searches through each album for a match. We search through each album and then in each song to see if the names of the parameter track and found track are similar enough to be deemed a match. We use startswith() to avoid potentially missing a song because of bad formatting done elsewhere.

We need to check if the track is performed by the specific artist desired to ensure that covers are not taken as the original song.

In [230]:
def attempt(track, artist, albums):
    uri = find_song(track, albums, artist)
    #Title Case
    if uri is None:
        track = track.lower()
        uri = find_song(titlecase(track), albums, artist)
    #lowercase
    if uri is None:
        uri = find_song(track.lower(), albums, artist)
    #First Word Capital
    if uri is None:
        uri = find_song(track.title(), albums, artist)
    #Uppercase
    if uri is None:
        uri = find_song(track.upper(), albums, artist)
    return uri

We define yet another helper function that attempts to find the parameter song in the found album uris with various potential formats. At each step, we change what is capitalized and attempt to find that song in the albums. Checking that artists match in find_song() becomes crucial here as the correct song may be found on the all uppercase attempt, but a cover may be found on the 20th album of the 3rd attempt.

The uri returned may be null, but this is handled in get_audio_features().

Additionally, it is worth noting that we should not do the same procedure for attempting different artist formats as each different formatting would prompt a new query to the Spotify API. Here, since we already have the album uris, it is not as expensive.

In [231]:
def get_uris(df):
    uris = []
    for _, row in df.iterrows():
        track = just_the_title(row['Song'])
        artist = just_the_artist(row['Artist'])
        albums = get_album_uris(artist)
        uri = attempt(track, artist, albums)
        uris.append(uri)
    return uris

We define one last helper method that takes in a dataframe and returns the track uris that correspond to tracks and artists given. It formats input using just_the_title() and just_the_artist() before attempting to find the correct uri.

Retrieving Data from Spotify

In [ ]:
uris = get_uris(df)
np.save('uris', uris)

We call get_uris() with the dataframe containing top 100 songs from the last 10 years. This is a lengthy process, so it makes sense to save the file locally to avoid needing to rerun to retrieve the same data.

In addition to the few cases mentioned before where an artist wouldn't be found, some other known drop cases include:

  • Songs that appear on an album or single whose 'artist' is a group or all parties involved and so nobody has direct ownership.
  • Songs with unusual capitalization like I hate U, I love U by gnash.
  • Songs that aren't on Spotify for one reason or another like eenie meenie by Sean Kingston.
  • Clean versions of explicit songs that have a completely different name on Billboard than on Spotify.
  • Miscellaneous mysterious drop cases that have no logical explanation like It Will Rain by Bruno Mars.

In the end, the above program retrieves about 95% of songs listed in the initial dataframe which is plenty for meaningful analysis.

Spotify's popularity metric is calculated on a scale from 1 to 100 based on the current year. Because of this, it is unsurprising to see a linear increase in general popularity as we go back. We attribute the generally high peaks across all 10 years to 'throwback hits' that still get played heavily for nostalgic value. The graph also reveals some outliers that must be considered for further analysis.

cs = ['red', 'green', 'yellow', 'blue', 'orange', 'purple', 'pink', 'teal', 'gray', 'black']
slopes = []
intercepts = []
for YEAR in range(2010, 2020):
    data_by_year = data[data['year'] == YEAR]
    first = np.percentile(data_by_year['popularity'], 15)
    last = np.percentile(data_by_year['popularity'], 85)
    small_data = data_by_year[(data_by_year['popularity'] >= first) & (data_by_year['popularity'] <= last)]

    x = small_data['popularity']
    y = small_data['billboard_rank']

    fit = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    fit_fn = np.poly1d(fit) 
    plt.plot(x, fit_fn(x), linewidth=2, color = cs[YEAR - 2010], label = "{}".format(YEAR))
    slopes.append(fit[0])
    intercepts.append(fit[1])
    print("{}; Slope: {}, Intercept: {}".format(YEAR, fit[0], fit[1]))

In [242]:
from random import seed
from random import random

s_fit = np.polyfit(years, slopes, 1)
i_fit = np.polyfit(years, intercepts, 1)
s_fit_fn = np.poly1d(s_fit)
i_fit_fn = np.poly1d(i_fit)

def billboard_rank_guesser(year):  
    def guess(x):
        return s_fit_fn(year) * x + i_fit_fn(year)
    return guess

seed(1)
for _ in range(10):
    value = int(random() * len(data.index - 1))
    test = data.iloc[value]
    test_pop = test.popularity
    act_rank = test.billboard_rank

    fn = billboard_rank_guesser(test.year)
    print("Rank prediction for {} by {} in {}: {}. Was actually: {}"
          .format(test.track, test.artist, test.year, fn(test_pop), act_rank))

We fit a new line of best fit to both slopes and intercepts given years. We can then define a function billboard_rank_guesser() that, given a year, can return a best fit function that in turn guesses billboard rank given spotify popularity.

The random test of 5 songs in the data shows expected results. Some songs are almost exactly spot on while some songs that experienced unusual changes in recent years are considerably off. After all, the 5 random songs could be outliers that we removed in finding this data.

Conclusion¶

In general, we found that other factors that are taken to account in Billboard's ranking either did not change much in this decade or have very little effect on their rank compared to raw plays. These factors include music video views, album sales and radio play. We can attribute this to the increasingly mobile nature of music. The portability of Spotify (and its competitors like Pandora and Apple Music) and the volume of play that allows becomes a strong indicator for general popularity.

Data Feature Analysis

Now we begin to analyze the role of each feature in determining the popularity of a song. This will allow us to run regression algorithms on our features that could predict the popularity of a song given its features, which we could then pipe into our previous algorithm to predict its billboard rank in a given year.

Linear Regression Coefficient Dataframe¶

We now create and run regression algorithms on our dataset to analyze each feature's impact on popularity.

In [248]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn import svm

linear_coef_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['year', 'popularity_intercept', 'danceability', 'energy', 'key', 'loudness', 'mode', 'speechiness', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence', 'tempo', 'duration_ms'])
svm_coef_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['year', 'popularity_intercept', 'danceability', 'energy', 'key', 'loudness', 'mode', 'speechiness', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence', 'tempo', 'duration_ms'])

for year in range(2010,2020):
    year_data = data[data['year']==year]
    X = year_data[['danceability', 'energy', 'key', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'mode', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence', 'tempo', 'duration_ms']]
    Y = year_data['popularity']
    
    linear_mdl = LinearRegression().fit(X, Y)
    linear_mdl.coef_ = np.insert(linear_mdl.coef_, 0, year)
    linear_mdl.coef_ = np.insert(linear_mdl.coef_, 1, linear_mdl.intercept_)
    linear_coef_df = linear_coef_df.append(pd.Series(linear_mdl.coef_, index=linear_coef_df.columns), ignore_index=True)
    
    svm_mdl = svm.SVR(kernel='linear').fit(X, Y)
    svm_coefs = svm_mdl.coef_[0]
    svm_coefs = np.insert(svm_coefs, 0, year)
    svm_coefs = np.insert(svm_coefs, 1, svm_mdl.intercept_)
    svm_coef_df = svm_coef_df.append(pd.Series(svm_coefs, index=svm_coef_df.columns), ignore_index=True)

We take a look at two linear regression algorithsm-- the standard Linear Regression algorithm with squared loss, and the Support Vector Regression algorithm, which uses optimized hyperplanes to separate the data in multiple dimensions.

Each of these graphs represents the change in correlation between each feature and year, and the second degree polynomial of best fit represent the general trend of impact each of these features has. For example a look at the Tempo graph tells us that in the years 2011 and 2013, an increase in tempo caused a decrease in popularity (because of the negative coefficient) but in every other year the two had a positive correlation. But more generally, over the 10 years, tempo has shifted from creating a negative impact on popularity to a positive impact on popularity. A similar analysis follows for Loudness where the years 2010-2012 saw a negative impact of loudness on popularity, but the later years so a positive impact, and the line of best fit indicates a general increase in the positive impact of loudness.

Comparing Various Regression Algorithms¶

In [252]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, train_test_split,cross_val_score
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

kfold = KFold(10, True, 1)
linear_avg = []
linear_svm_avg = []
svm_avg = []
knn_avg = []

data = data[['year', 'popularity', 'danceability', 'energy', 'key', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'mode', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence', 'tempo', 'duration_ms']]
data = data.reset_index(drop=True)
X = data.drop(['popularity'], axis=1)
Y = data['popularity']

for train, test in kfold.split(X):
    X_train, X_test = X.loc[train, :], X.loc[test, :]
    y_train, y_test = Y[train], Y[test]

    svm_mdl = svm.SVR(gamma='auto').fit(X_train, y_train)
    svm_acc = svm_mdl.score(X_test, y_test)

    linear_mdl = LinearRegression().fit(X_train, y_train)
    linear_acc = linear_mdl.score(X_test, y_test)

    knn_mdl = KNeighborsClassifier().fit(X_train, y_train)
    knn_acc = knn_mdl.score(X_test, y_test)

    linear_avg.append(linear_acc)
    svm_avg.append(svm_acc)
    knn_avg.append(knn_acc)

print("linear acc ", np.mean(linear_avg))
print("svm acc ", np.mean(svm_avg))
print("knn acc ", np.mean(knn_avg))

linear acc  0.265743475741396
svm acc  0.0069820320428157666
knn acc  0.028611422172452404

From the above results, we determine that the linear classifier performs with the best accuracy of the three regression algorithms. Thus, we continue our prediction with the linear model by using sklearn's LinearRegression.

features = ['year', 'danceability', 'energy', 'key', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'mode', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence', 'tempo', 'duration_ms']
def predict_popularity(song):
    song = song[features]
    return linear_mdl.predict(song)

This function takes in a song from the dataframe and strips it down to just the features, which it then sends to the prediction model to predict the song's popularity given its year and musical features.

Conclusion

Despite our best efforts to predict what makes a song good using its features, it's unfortunately a much harder task than it seems at first glance. Due to the nature of music, a pop song's popularity is heavily dependent on factors regarding the state of the human population at any given time rather than the song's musicality. Descriptors are valuable, but they say little about the mood of the population and the music they want because of it. Online streaming allows for people to have access to whatever music they find appealing, so the anatomy of a pop song is no longer strictly one formula or even resembling it.

Our models do predict that any given pop song will probably fall in the 40-60 ranking in Billboard, which is an expected conclusion due to viral success coming from a wide variety of variables both quantitive and qualitative. Most songs fall into the 'average' of whatever set we are getting them from.

To answer the initial question, it's not possible to reverse engineer a pop song purely on numbers. Music is a little more complex than that.
